<DOCNO> AP880430-0003 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
opec moved one major step closer today to 
an agreement that could slightly increase oil prices and set the 
stage for closer coordination with oil producers outside its ranks 
but clinching the deal required the approval of oil ministers 
from saudi arabia and its three persian gulf arab allies who said 
they needed to consult their governments first 
a meeting of all opec oil ministers was set for tonight at 
cartel headquarters but it was not certain a final decision would 
be made then 
eight of the 13 members of the organization of petroleum 
exporting countries agreed in a meeting that ended early today to a 
proposed 2 percent cut in opecs total oil production according to 
oil ministers from iran and venezuela 
the cuts would be for may and june only said venezuelan oil 
minister arturo hernandez grisanti 
the saudis earlier indicated they opposed production cuts 
believing prices would rebound soon anyway since oil demand is 
likely to rise this summer 
saudi king fahd said in a newspaper interview thursday that opec 
should simply stick to its current set of production quotas which 
often are exceeded he did not explicitly rule out cuts as small as 
those proposed in vienna 
besides saudi arabia the others saying they wanted to think it 
over were kuwait qatar and the united arab emirates 
iraq which is not party to opecs existing agreement on 
production limits was not expected to take part in the proposed 
cuts hernandez said 
the eight that tentatively accepted the deal this morning were 
iran algeria libya nigeria gabon venezuela ecuador and 
indonesia the proposal was put on the table by algeria 
the proposed cuts in output in conjunction with similarly small 
cuts by a group of six independent oilproducing nations would 
remove a total of 500000 barrels a day from the world oil market 
the goal is to lift oil prices to opecs target of 18 a 
42gallon barrel from the range now of between 14 and 16 
oil prices on the open market moved erratically in nervous 
trading friday prices fell more than 60 cents a barrel in europe 
but recovered in later us trading 
on the new york mercantile exchange june contracts for west 
texas intermediate the main us grade of oil closed at 1799 a 
barrel up one cent from thursday at one point the price was off 
43 cents but then recovered 
the proposed opec cuts are so small that analysts said the main 
effect on the market would be psychological for opec the 
principal benefit would be establishing closer ties to rival oil 
producers who in recent years have weakened opec by taking away 
its market share 
opec and nonopec producers have never before formally agreed to 
mutual cuts in production although mexico has informally sought to 
align its policies with opec 
the nonopec countries involved in the current proposal are 
mexico egypt china oman malaysia and angola 
representatives of these independent producers were in vienna 
earlier this week for talks with a committee of six opec oil 
ministers they left before opecs meeting began thursday so it 
was not immediately clear if they would be satisfied with the 
proposed cut of 2 percent or 300000 barrels a day in opec 
production 
the nonopec group stipulated it would cut its oil exports by 5 
percent or 200000 barrels a day only if opec made similar 
proportional reductions it was not more precise about the 
reciprocity 
regardless of the outcome of the talks on production cuts opec 
intended to step up contacts with the nonopec group in hopes of 
establishing a regular dialogue that could lead to more 
coordination of production and pricing policy in the future 
several oil ministers said 
we must send a positive signal to them said gholamreza 
aghazadeh the oil minister of iran 
</TEXT>
