<TEXT>
a senate ethics panel says comments by sen 
david durenberger on an espionage case hurt relations between 
congress and intelligence agencies but durenberger says the harm 
already had been done by the late cia chief william casey 
durenberger was chastised friday by the senate ethics committee 
as it closed an investigation that began last year after the 
minnesota republican publicly discussed an espionage case involving 
the united states and israel 
the committee told durenberger in a letter the ethics 
committee has determined that your statements gave the appearance 
that you were disclosing sensitive national security information 
and such appearance jeopardized the mutual confidence which must 
exist between the congress and the intelligence community 
because the committee has concluded that your actions were not 
intentional deliberate nor attended with gross negligence and 
because of the particular facts of this case we will not recommend 
that the senate take institutional action against you however the 
committee wants to make it clear that it does not condone your 
actions 
the ethics investigation centered on comments durenberger made 
at an event sponsored by the american israel public affairs 
committee in palm beach fla on march 15 1987 
durenberger reportedly disclosed to the group that casey in 1982 
had changed the rules under which allies did not spy on each 
other by recruiting an israeli military officer to spy on israel 
for the united states 
durenbergers comments were said to be aimed at giving context 
to the case of jonathan jay pollard an american convicted of 
spying on the united states for israel 
durenberger said he based his remarks on newspaper accounts and 
maintained that he exercised due care in preparation for the 
speech 
the former chairman of the select committee on intelligence 
issued a statement saying he was pleased that the committee had 
concluded its investigation and determined that no action was 
necessary but he added 
the late cia director william caseys fundamental disagreement 
over the philosophy of congressional oversight led to frequent 
clashes with the intelligence committee 
director casey was a strong leader loyal to his own view of 
the public interest but his belief that congress should play 
little or no role in intelligence oversight led to a lack of mutual 
confidence long before march 1987 
he added i respectfully disagree with the ethic committees 
conclusion that my statements gave the appearance that i was 
disclosing sensitive information 
sources present at the palm beach meeting and who said they took 
careful notes reported that durenberger said the cia recruited its 
israeli spy after israels 1982 invasion of lebanon the spy passed 
along sensitive information about the invasion durenberger 
reportedly told the group 
in a separate statement friday senate minority leader bob dole 
rkan said durenberger was an excellent chairman during one of 
the most demanding and crucial periods for intelligence oversight 
i had just as much confidence in dave before the ethics committee 
examination as i do right now 
the ethics committee letter was signed by sens howell heflin 
dala david pryor dark terry sanford dnc warren rudman 
rnh jesse helms rnc and nancy kassebaum rkan 
</TEXT>
