injuries when those guns are used 
the legal issue was referred friday to the district of columbia 
court of appeals in a case involving thomas k delahanty a former 
district of columbia policeman one of three people wounded by 
presidential assailant john w hinckley jr in the 1981 shooting 
delahanty had tried to sue the gun manufacturer 
the action by the us circuit court of appeals in washington 
raises the possibility that delahanty and former white house press 
secretary james brady may revive lawsuits against roehm 
gesellschaft the west german manufacturer of the 22caliber 
pistol used by hinckley 
the federal court sought the dc courts view because federal 
courts must apply the laws of the states in which they are located 
to civil suits 
the court noted that maryland law should be consulted since the 
district of columbia was carved out of maryland when the nations 
capital was formed 
a 1985 ruling by marylands highest court made gun makers and 
sellers liable for injuries and death caused by the criminal use of 
socalled saturday night specials 
the federal courts requst an advisory opinion is merely a 
suggestion and does not require a ruling by the dc court 
richard gardiner assistant general counsel of the national 
