<TEXT>
irving kolodin one of the first music critics 
to pay extensive attention to phonograph records has died after 
suffering a stroke one year ago he was 80 years old 
kolodin who died friday in a manhattan nursing home wrote 
prolifically about a wide range of musical styles ranging from 
classical to jazz 
he joined the new york sun in 1932 and became its chief critic 
before leaving in 1950 his first book of phonograph record reviews 
appeared in 1941 
over the course of his career kolodin was music critic for the 
saturday review from 1947 to 1982 and historian of the metropolitan 
opera publishing his first book on the company in 1936 
he was working on an edition tracing the first 100 years of the 
metropolitan when he suffered a debilitating stroke in 1987 
in 1970 kolodin selected the classical music for the first 
official white housw music library he also taught criticism at the 
juilliard school from 1968 to 1982 
kolodin was married from 1936 to 1970 to the former irma rose 
levy and is survived by two stepchildren information on funeral 
arrangements was not immediately available 
