<TEXT>
from george bushs viewpoint the american 
economy couldnt be friendlier consumer spending is booming 
unemployment falling and the prospects of inflation too ethereal to 
stir much worry 
in fact the economys prospects appear so bright that one 
leading economic forecasting firm has an economic model showing 
bush will win the presidency on nov 8 with 53 percent of the vote 
that forecast by data resources inc uses a computer model which 
combines what is already known about the economys performance over 
the past six months with the firms expectations for growth and 
inflation between now and election day 
using an economic model to forecast an election still six months 
may be going out on a limb but economists said the exercise does 
highlight the importance economic issues play in voters decisions 
the model has been correct in the past people do vote their 
pocketbooks said david wyss chief financial economist at dri 
when things are going well they want more of the same and that 
is what mr bush is promising 
at the start of the year things did not look as promising for 
the republicans the 508point stock market plunge on oct 19 had 
spawned widespread fears that the country would fall into a 
recession in the early part of 1988 
in the three months following the collapse consumer spending 
fell by the biggest amount since 1980 when jimmy carter was 
president consumer spending accounts for twothrids of overall 
economic activity and that decline toppled the country into a 
brief recession which is cited as one of the factors leading to 
carters reelection defeat 
but this time around the economy kept rolling the government 
reported last tuesday that consumer spending propelled by strong 
auto sales rebounded nicely in the first three months of the year 
providing the momentum for 23 percent growth in the overall 
economy as measured by the gross national product 
the economic expansion which has now lasted for a peacetime 
record of 64 months has driven the unemployment rate down to a 
nineyear low of 56 percent 
the unexpectedly strong growth this year and the big gains in 
employment are raising some concerns that inflation is about to 
become a problem again economists are worried that with job 
markets growing tight and many industries operating at high 
capacity rates demand will start to push prices higher 
prices at both the retail and wholesale levels took a big jump 
up in march raising fears in financial markets that the federal 
reserve will be forced to step in with a dose of higher interest 
rates aimed at cooling off demand 
some analysts believe the central bank has already tightened 
slightly and they predict interest rates will be pushed up another 
notch if next fridays unemployment report shows the jobless rate 
dipped further to 55 percent in april 
but many analysts believe the increases in inflation and 
interest rates likely to occur over the next six months will be so 
small that they wont prove worrisome to voters 
donald straszheim chief economist at merrill lynch predicted 
that interest rates will only increase by onehalf to one full 
percentage point and this will not be enough to curb what he 
expects will be generally good economic growth this year 
if the economy does as well as expected between now and 
november that should be awfully good news for the republicans 
because presidents get the credit or the blame for the economys 
performance whether they deserve it or not straszheim said 
the democrats can be expected to try to focus the campaign on 
such problems as the huge budget and trade deficits and the unease 
americans feel about the countrys slide in the past eight years 
into the status of the worlds leading debtor nation 
questions about whether the united states will be able to 
compete in the future and what americans living standards will be 
should affect the outcome as well said lawrence chimerine 
president of the wefa group another economist forecasting firm 
but other analysts said these issues remain distant abstractions 
when compared to such pocketbook matters as jobs and inflation 
analysts also said that president reagans exceptional luck with 
the economy appears to be rubbing off on his vice president 
while the country had to endure the steepest recession since the 
depression in 198182 the recovery was well underway by the time 
reagan had to run for reelection 
many economists are predicting the next downturn will begin in 
1989 leaving plenty of time for the recovery to start before the 
next presidential election 
it is almost magical the way the economy has performed the 
right way for reagan at just the right time said allen sinai 
chief economist of the boston co bush is a lucky man to be 
second in line to the luck of the irish 
