the strikebreaking ferries slipped their moorings showed that the 
union still has clout 
moreover ships officers are wary of sailing with nonunion 
crews and picket lines discourage potential ferry passengers 
the conservative governments law that makes unions liable for 
damages over sympathy strikes is the one that helped crack 
prolonged and often violent stoppages by newspaper production 
unions and coal miners 
