<TEXT>
here is the text of the democratic response 
given saturday by rep don j pease dohio to president reagans 
radio address 
president reagan ought to sign the trade bill he will make a 
foolish mistake if he vetoes the bill it will be a foolish mistake 
because the united states is on the threshold of a new economic 
era to preserve our standard of living in the 1990s we must do 
better much better in the game of global trade 
the american people understand this thats why the trade bill 
passed the congress by a large bipartisan majority 
the bill recognizes that we need to do two things above all we 
must launch an export campaign unprecedented in our history and we 
must improve our productivity 
the bill plots a strategy for increasing exports first it 
liberates firms from the red tape of unduly tight export controls 
second it boosts export promotion efforts to benefit american 
companies third it blows the whistle on unequal and unfair trade 
many countries have gotten rich off of free access to the us 
market while protecting their home markets these countries can now 
afford to eliminate their trade barriers the bill requires them to 
live up to their international obligations pure and simple we 
seek a level playing field 
but it takes more than a level playing field to compete youve 
got to have skilled employees and a sure way to boost labor 
productivity is to strengthen education and training 
the trade bill would entitle all workers who lose their jobs to 
imports to training or remedial education it provides nearly a 
billion dollars for the readjustment of other workers and it 
renews the nations commitment to math science foreign language 
and vocational education 
in addition the bill requires large financially sound 
companies to give their employees and communities 60 days notice of 
plant closings or mass layoffs it merely calls for a measure of 
common courtesy on the part of those companies that can afford it 
members of congress get 60 days notice when they lose their job 
so does the president of the united states why shouldnt ordinary 
citizens even president reagans own task force and the us 
chamber of commerce say that advance notice is good business 
practice 
the president objects because he believes this is a matter for 
the private sector not the government to decide well mr 
president the private sector has had every opportunity to take 
care of this problem on its own terms it has failed 
onethird of all workers get no notice theyre told to pick up 
their paychecks and leave twothirds of all workers get less than 
two weeks notice they may have put in 20 years of service and 
have two kids in college but theyre out of the street just like 
that 
years ago the american people decided that it makes sense to 
ease the social and economic costs of unrestrained free enterprise 
we enacted child labor minimum wage and antitrust laws the plant 
closing provision is squarely in this tradition 
critics say the provision has nothing to do with competitveness 
theyre wrong if a worker had advance notice of a layoff he has 
time to make arrangements for retraining before the clock starts 
ticking on his unemployment insurance reducing the period of 
unemployment facilitating retraining that is what improving labor 
productivity is all about 
today america needs a workforce that is flexible and adaptable 
able to shift rapidly to changing economic conditions germany and 
japan have already figured this out they have advancenotice 
requirements to oppose this provision is to resist an effort to 
move this country into the 1990s 
it is tragic that the president is threatening to kill the 
entire bipartisan trade bill on account of this one provision in 
truth his opposition is really based on symbolism he fears a 
symbolic victory for labor 
is mere symbolism worth the price of needlessly unemployed 
people and depressed communities is it worth the price of another 
several years without a coherent foreign economic policy is it 
worth killing a bipartisan bill which congress spent three years 
on common sense says no 
mr president the country is ready for the 1990s for the sake 
of the american people sign the trade bill 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

