an epidemic of meningitis in central 
and western africa has affected thousands of people and killed 
hundreds but vaccination programs are controlling the spread 
according to a united nations agency 
a unicef report was obtained saturday by the associated press 
it said that in chad 4211 cases of the disease including 400 
deaths were reported as of wednesday 
the epidemic has ended in the capital ndjamena but was 
continuing in chads northern desert regions the report said 
it said more than 800000 chadians have been vaccinated with 
coverage in the capital reaching 95 percent 
on friday chads southern neighbor cameroon reported 300 
cases of meningitis with 40 deaths in its northernmost province 
cameroon radio said the epidemic was spread by people entering 
cameroon from chad 
unicef also reported 372 cases of meningitis and 58 deaths in 
the west african country of benin and said a vaccination campaign 
was under way 
benins northern neighbors burkina faso and niger also are 
affected the report said 
meningitis is an inflammation of the membranes surrounding the 
brain and spinal cord as the result of infection by bacteria or 
viruses 
