<TEXT>
two former underground solidarity leaders 
were released from prison saturday and flew to rome after initially 
refusing to leave the country 
kornel morawiecki 46 and andrzej kolodziej 28 were put on a 
plane to vienna austria and arrived in rome saturday night 
the communist government released the two men from warsaws 
rakowiecka prison saturday in a deal with roman catholic church 
officials 
morawiecki and kolodziej had been driven to warsaws airport to 
board a flight for rome but the two refused to leave after meeting 
with family members at the airport 
the two were then taken back to the prison but agreed to leave 
the country after more talks at the prison involving church 
officials 
one of morawieckis daughters marta said the two men were told 
they could either leave together or remain imprisoned she said 
medical reasons played a role in the decision to leave 
the two were given multiple exitandentry passports and were 
expected to undergo medical treatment in rome both apparently are 
suffering from ulcers and other medical problems 
morawiecki who was arrested nov 9 1987 was chairman of the 
militant splinter group fighting solidarity 
he went underground after martial law was declared in december 
1981 and the solidarity union federation was suspended and 
subsequently outlawed in 1982 he formed fighting solidarity 
which differs from solidarity because it advocates anticommunist 
political goals solidarity emphasizes social and union issues 
kolodziej headed fighting solidarity from the time of 
morawieckis arrest until his own capture in january he had been 
in hiding since 1985 
a third less prominent fighting solidarity activist krzystof 
szymanski also was released saturday 
morawieckis elder daughter anna said morawiecki and kolodziej 
had agreed to leave the country in a deal worked out by church 
officials but after family members at the airport told them about 
new strikes in the country they decided to stay 
asked to explain what finally prompted the two men to leave 
marta morawiecki said we cannot give you a full explanation 
there were very important arguments and they both finally agreed to 
go 
there were some personal reasons which had to be taken into 
account also a serious danger to kolodziejs health she said 
ewa maria stoja kolodziejs girlfriend said official documents 
indicated the two men were being released at the recommendation of 
a commission of prison doctors due to the required urgent medical 
examination which may also take place abroad 
she said kolodziej suffered from ulcers and teeth problems 
while morawiecki had ulcer symptoms poor eyesight and heart and 
kidney problems 
morawiecki speaking with reporters in rome said he and 
kolodziej at first did not want to leave poland because they were 
not told why they were being sent to the west he said the issue 
was settled after they spoke with a secretary of the polish 
episcopal conference aloizj orszulik 
we decided to leave for three reasons he said first the 
medical diagnosis that koldziej might have a tumor secondly 
the possibility that it might be more difficult in the future for 
the polish church to perform these humanitarian acts if we refused 
and lastly the assurance that we would be allowed to return 
whenever we choose 
morawiecki said that while in prison he was never told anything 
about what was happening in the country 
i only learned something today he said there is an 
agitation going on that reminds me of august of 1980 i believe 
this pressure will increase and i hope it might lead to a change in 
government 
in august 1980 nationwide strikes led to the creation of 
solidarity it was chartered by the government and became the first 
independent union federation in the soviet bloc but was banned 
after the december 1981 crackdown 
authorities alleged that morawiecki and kolodziej were part of a 
ring that attempted to smuggle equipment intended for terrorist use 
from sweden they were never formally charged 
in a statement in november kolodziej denied the allegations 
in september 1986 the communist government issued a broad 
amnesty for political prisoners since then all political 
activists jailed have been held on criminal charges 
in another development jan andrzej gorny the solidarity leader 
in the southern silesian industrial region was released after an 
appeals court on friday suspended his sentence solidarity sources 
said 
gorny was serving an 18month sentence at a prison in katowice 
after being convicted of failing to pay alimony and using false 
identity cards he staged a hunger strike in february to protest 
against his sentence 
