<TEXT>
a federal judge has ordered the immigration 
and naturalization service not to use coercion to keep salvadoran 
refugees from applying for political asylum 
in a ruling released late friday us district judge david v 
kenyon granted a petition for a permanent injunction ordering the 
ins to routinely inform all salvadorans detained that they have a 
right to ask for political asylum legal counsel and even access to 
pay telephones 
the ruling reaffirmed a preliminary injunction kenyon issued in 
1982 in which he ruled that the ins routinely threatened 
salvadorans to talk them out of their rights ins attorneys had 
denied many of the allegations of abuses 
civil rights attorneys hailed the ruling 
the decision really affirms the fact that salvadorans with 
valid claims were simply being denied justice said linton 
joaquin executive director of the central american refugee center 
who helped argue the classaction lawsuit 
the governments lead attorney in the case allen hausman 
criticized the decision saying it offered sweeping protections to 
salvadorans that are not enjoyed by other immigrants 
how can you say a person from haiti or south africa or iran is 
less deserving its hard to distinguish said hausman assistant 
director of the justice departments office of immigration 
litigation in washington 
the attorney said he didnt know if the ins would appeal 
kenyons decision came after a twoyear nonjury trial that 
featured testimony from 180 witnesses including many immigrants 
who said they had been tortured in their native country 
the total number of salvadorans who have applied for asylum was 
not available but the ins said late last year it was considering 
about 25000 applications from salvadorans in los angeles more 
than half of the estimated 750000 salvadorans living in the united 
states are in the los angeles area 
during the 1985 fiscal year 74 salvadorans were granted 
political asylum in the united states and 2229 had their 
application rejected during the same period 2779 iranians and 
408 nicaraguans were granted asylum 
the reagan administration maintains that many of the salvadorans 
do not qualify because they are economic immigrants fleeing poverty 
rather than political refugees fleeing persecution 
 
