<TEXT>
the onceinfouryears general conference of 
the united methodist church ended the first lap saturday of a 
concentrated exercise in ecclesiastical democracy 
like most us protestant bodies the churchs organizational 
system is modeled on the nations representative system and the 
process here provided an intensified example of it 
so far it has been preoccupied with preliminary hearings of 
legislative committees on a range of proposals including the 
status of homosexuals in the united methodist church and a new 
hymnbook decisions will come next week in the second stage of the 
11day conference which runs through friday 
the group is the top lawmaking body for the approximately 10 
million united methodists in the country who make up the nations 
secondlargest protestant denomination after the southern baptists 
they elect from their regional units the 996 national 
delegates half laity and half clergy in a sense they resemble 
legislators sent by states to congress 
somewhat like the congressional record a daily similarlooking 
publication the daily christian advocate provides a verbatim 
account of general proceedings and a summary of committee 
deliberations 
there is lobbying here too including advocates in the 
cervantes convention center hallways who passed out buttons and 
brochures promoting church establishment of a university in africa 
that project costing an estimated 20 million and to be located 
in zimbabwe was approved by the conference saturday 
as in the secular political realm the conferences task 
involves carving out budgets and a 14 percent increase is being 
proposed to 100 million annually for national operations that 
doesnt include the approximately 25 billion given annually for 
local and regional activities 
alongside the general conference or legislative branch the 
churchs approximately 100 area bishops serve as the executive 
branch appointing clergy to pastoral or other duties 
the church also has 13 national boards or agencies somewhat 
like cabinetlevel departments 
bishops have no vote at the legislative conference but are 
required to be present address it and in rotation preside over 
it 
in addition to the legislative and executive branches a 
ninemember judicial council elected by the conference serves as 
the churchs supreme court to settle disputes over church law 
or constitution the council has a rigorous schedule during the 
general conference 
the cost of the gathering about 25 million including the 
convention hall rental fee the delegates air travel and 55 each 
per day for living expenses 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

