<TEXT>
congress turned its spotlight of scrutiny on 
junk bonds this past week and the head of the investment firm 
that pioneered the controversial issues defended them staunchly 
in 6 hours of testimony thursday before a house investigative 
subcommittee frederick h joseph the chief executive of drexel 
burnham lambert inc also defended the firm against allegations of 
manipulation of the 160 billion junk bond market 
drexel a leading wall street investment firm is the granddaddy 
of the highyield highrisk bonds and underwrites around 40 
percent of all junk bonds issued 
the securities are designed to allow companies without a track 
record of earnings to get financing based on whether they have 
sufficient cash flow to pay off their debts they pay higher 
interest rates than those of established companies and are viewed 
as riskier investments 
michael milken chief of drexels junk bond trading unit in 
beverly hills calif who pioneered the bonds was a lot less 
talkative than joseph at a hearing wednesday before the 
investigations subcommittee of the house energy and commerce 
committee 
milken who has been under investigation for the past year and a 
half by a federal grand jury that is reported to be probing insider 
trading refused to testify and cited his fifth amendment 
protection against selfincrimination 
behind the spotlight the junk bond market seems to have quietly 
risen like a phoenix from the ashes of the october stock market 
collapse as worries about a recession have subsided 
the resurgence of corporate takeover fever earlier this year 
also gave junk bonds a shot in the arm since many of the issues 
are used to finance acquisitions 
some of the companies that have used junk bond financing such 
as businesses in the steel and chemical industries have performed 
well recently helped by a weaker dollar that made their exports 
more attractive after the crash there had been concern that 
failures of vulnerable companies could cast a shadow on the junk 
bond market 
theres an ongoing need for highyield securities said 
robert waill a managing director of investment firm lf 
rothschild amp co and the head of its junk bond research department 
waill believes more funds will be attracted to junk bonds in the 
coming months as investors switch big sums of money now parked in 
moneymarket funds into highyield mutual funds featuring junk 
bonds the moneymarket funds based on prevailing interest rates 
on treasury bonds have been yielding relatively low returns 
recently 
junk bonds are purchased mainly by big financial institutions 
and most individual investors buy them through highyield mutual 
funds 
the bad publicity now surrounding the bonds with congressional 
investigators portraying drexel as a greedy firm that elbowed its 
own clients aside so top employees could profit on hot new issues 
wont hurt the market traders insist 
this has been going on for 18 months its a little 
anticlimactic by now waill said referring to investigations of 
junk bond trading and the congressional hearings 
drexels joseph told the house panel he expects the junk bond 
market to expand substantially over the next 10 years since less 
than 10 percent of the companies that could get financing by 
issuing the highyield bonds have done so 
in the last 10 years the market has grown explosively from 
less than 25 billion in junk bonds in 1977 to around 160 billion 
last year or 25 percent of the 650 billion corporate debt market 
joseph pointed to cable television as an example of an industry 
ripe for the bonds saying cable companies tend to have low 
earnings because of their high investment costs initially but also 
have great profit potential 
the average company issuing junk bonds is about 36 years old 
has around 1 billion in assets and employs more than 4000 people 
drexel says 
</TEXT>
