<TEXT>
a double dose of good economic news failed to inspire the 
nations financial markets which worried more about inflation and 
ended the week by heading down 
the commerce department said friday that its index of leading 
indicators rose 08 percent in march the second straight big 
monthly gain some economists said the figure eliminated chances of 
a recession in 1988 and thereby boosted the republican chances for 
winning the presidential election 
new home sales also rose in march for the second straight month 
the commerce department said the 4 percent gain strengthened 
arguments that the housing industry has revived following a slump 
in the aftermath of the october stock market crash 
nevertheless some analysts said the sales level could fade 
later this year because of rising mortgage rates a consequence of 
a slow upward move in interest rates over the past several weeks 
others said economic strength also means a probable rise in 
inflation which could compel the federal reserve to tighten credit 
conditions 
it is the rise in inflation that worries investors in the stock 
and bond markets which largely ignored the news on the economy 
friday and instead retreated 
on wall street the dow jones average of 30 industrial stocks 
dropped 895 points to 203233 
in the bond market a sensitive barometer of inflation and 
interest rate trends the key 30year treasury bond lost about 
125 in face amount and its yield edged up slightly to 909 
percent 
the economic news helped the value of the dollar which rose 
slightly against most key currencies but some traders said the 
dollars behavior also was a reaction to the evidence of rising 
interest rates which makes dollardenominated assets more valuable 
